        <section class="container mt-4 pt-5" style="padding-top: 80px;">
            <h2 class="text-center">Inventory Tracker</h2>
            <p class="text-center">This project is a full-stack Inventory Tracker Web Application built using Node.js, Express, MySQL, and
                EJS, designed to manage inventory and streamline item borrowing. It supports role-based access with
                admin and user privileges, allowing admins to manage items and users to browse, borrow, and track items.
            </p>
            <br>
            <img src="/images/inventoryTracker.png" alt="My Photo" class="img-fluid d-block mx-auto my-3">

            <p>This project is a full-featured Inventory Tracker Web App built with Node.js, Express, MySQL, and EJS. It
                allows users to register, log in, browse inventory, borrow items, and manage their profiles. Admins can
                add, update, and delete items, including uploading images. The app features session-based
                authentication, flash messages for validation and feedback, and an intuitive Bootstrap-powered UI for
                seamless interaction.</p>
            <p>The Inventory Tracker app demonstrates the fundamentals of server-side development using Node.js,
                Express, MySQL, and EJS.</p>
            <p>It includes:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>User authentication (login, registration, hashed passwords)</li>
                <li>Session management for storing login state and borrowed items</li>
                <li>Role-based access control (admin vs regular user)</li>
                <li>CRUD operations for inventory items</li>
                <li>Dynamic HTML rendering with EJS templates</li>
                <li>Form handling for adding, updating, and borrowing items</li>
                <li>Image upload using multer</li>
                <li>MySQL database integration</li>
                <li>Bootstrap</li>
                <li>RESTful route structure</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This app uses a real database (MySQL) to store users, items, and borrowed records, providing a more
                realistic experience compared to in-memory learning apps.</p>

            <p>What I Learned:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Setting up and connecting Node.js with MySQL</li>
                <li>Implementing authentication and session-based login</li>
                <li>Handling file uploads safely with multer</li>
                <li>Creating dynamic views with EJS and rendering SQL data</li>
                <li>Designing a simple borrowing workflow and updating inventory logic</li>
                <li>Working with Express middleware for security and cleaner code structure</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
